          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">German right-wing victory</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-jan-31-2.png" alt="German right-wing victory" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;"><strong>Summary: The German center-right and far-right banded together to pass a motion for stricter immigration policies.</strong></p>

          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The German parliament (Bundestag) <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-01-2025-h2-5-narrowly-passed?source=website" target="_blank">narrowly passed</a> a resolution for stricter rules on immigration. The nonbinding resolution urges permanent border controls, immediate detention of rejected asylum seekers, and more deportation centers. It argues that asylum seekers should be turned away if arriving from safe EU countries. Friedrich Merz plans to propose actual legislation on Friday.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The motion also calls for reversing Germany’s recent laws allowing dual citizenship, which was only allowed in 2024. MPS passed this with 348 -345, with 10 absentations. The motion, introduced by the center-right CDU and backed by the far-right AFD, received some votes from the FDP, making it pass. It was controversial as it broke the CDU's promise to oppose the AFD party.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The move has sparked intense political debate ahead of the February 23 elections. Chancellor Scholz’s SPD and the Greens strongly oppose it, citing conflicts with EU asylum laws. Former German Chancellor Angela Merkel <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-01-2025-h2-6-criticized-the-cdu?source=website" target="_blank">criticized the CDU</a> for voting along with AFD on this issue.</p>
        </mj-text>
