          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Rohingya boat aground Aceh</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;"><strong>Summary: A boatful of Rohingya refugees arrived in the Indonesian province of Aceh while trying to get to Malaysia.</strong></p>

          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">
          More than 70 Rohingya refugees <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-01-2025-h3-7-arrived-on-a-beach?source=website" target="_blank">arrived on a beach</a> in Indonesia's Aceh province after their boat ran aground due to engine failure. The vessel, carrying 40 men, 32 women, and four children, was reportedly damaged by traffickers before setting sail from Cox's Bazar, Bangladesh, aiming for Malaysia. 
</p>
<p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">
          Locals initially blocked their arrival; the refugees were allowed to land after police intervention. Over 2,000 Rohingya reached Indonesia in 2023, surpassing previous years' totals. Rohingya have often received <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-01-2025-h3-8-hostile-treatment?source=website" target="_blank">hostile treatment</a> in Indonesia, bringing a lot of criticism from Human Rights groups.
</p>
<p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">
         The Rohingya, a persecuted Muslim minority in Myanmar, have faced violence and displacement from Myanmar, with around one million currently <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-01-2025-h3-9-living-in-camps?source=website" target="_blank">living in camps</a> in Bangladesh. Many fled following a brutal 2017 crackdown by Myanmar's military, accused of mass killings and rapes, and many continue to flee as crackdowns have worsened again.
</p>
        </mj-text>
