          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">
          <strong>🇷🇺 Russia quiet on Syrian request to extradite Assad</strong> 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Kremlin spokesperson Dmitry Peskov <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-01-2025-br2-11-refused-to-comment?source=website" target="_blank">refused to comment</a> on reports that Syria’s new government wants Russia to extradite former President Bashar Assad in exchange for maintaining its military bases. The request reportedly came from Syria’s new leader, Ahmed al-Sharaa, during a Russian delegation’s visit to Damascus. “I will leave this without any comments. We will continue further dialogue with the Syrian authorities,” Peskov said.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Assad was granted asylum in Russia after fleeing there in December. Al-Sharaa also urged Russia to rebuild trust with the Syrian people through compensation and reconstruction. Russia played a key role in supporting Assad’s regime through military intervention but is now evacuating equipment from Syrian bases, especially after Syria canceled Russia’s long-term naval lease at Tartus, downgrading the status of Russian-Syrian relations.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
